0","Abt 1270":"circa 1270","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Schotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1270–5 February 1330":"about 1270–5 February 1330","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1302–Male":"1302–Deceased","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1258–1258":"1258–1258","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","5 February 1330":"5 February 1330","about 1302":"about 1302","about 1313":"about 1313","about 1300":"about 1300","Abt 1270":"about 1270","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oliphant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London) and Scottish (Fife): from Old French <i>olifard</i> or <i>olifant</i>, of uncertain meaning. It has been suggested that this might be a derivative of Old French <i>olif</i> ‘olive’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i> ‘derisive nickname for one who preferred an olive branch to more martial weapons’; it may have denoted a man twisted like an olive-tree. The variant <i>Olifant</i> may have resulted from the substitution in Old Norman French of the sequence <i>l-r</i> by <i>l-n</i>, leading to a false association with Old French <i>olifant</i> ‘elephant’. This heraldic beast appears in the Scottish family's coats of arms. Branches of the Anglo-Norman family owned lands in both England and Scotland. The surname is now chiefly Scottish.","English: possibly a topographic name from residence at an inn known as the <i>Olyphaunt</i> or ‘elephant’, though whether this gave rise to a hereditary surname is unknown."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Oliphant Lord of Aberdalgie was born about 1270, his father, Sir Philip Olifard, was 51 and his mother, Isabella Douglas, was 13. He had at least 4 sons with Isabel Douglas. He died on 5 February 1330, in Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 61."},"et":{"Abt 1270–5 February 1330":"umbes 1270–5. veebruar 1330","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1258–1258":"1258–1258","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","5 February 1330":"5. veebruar 1330","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1313":"umbes 1313","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1270–5 February 1330":"noin 1270–5. helmikuuta 1330","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1258–1258":"1258–1258","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","5 February 1330":"5. helmikuuta 1330"